  <section id="no-ubuntu">
    <title>Can I install <app>Ubuntu</app>?</title>

    <p>Popular distributions have not been recommended in this tutorial. Further more, even distributions that do carry <app>GNOME</app> desktop by default have not been recommended too. The following table reasons why:</p>

    <table frame="all" rules="rows cols">
      <title>Table: Reasons why popular distributions have not been recommended</title>
      <tr>
        <td><p>Distribution Name</p></td>
        <td><p>Current Stable Release Number</p></td>
        <td><p>Carries GNOME? If Yes, Version?</p></td>
        <td><p>Details</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><p><app>Ubuntu</app></p></td>
        <td><p>13.10</p></td>
        <td><p>No</p></td>
        <td><p>It's default desktop is <app>Unity</app>.</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><p><app>LinuxMint</app></p></td>
        <td><p>15</p></td>
        <td><p>No</p></td>
        <td><p>Disk images that carry <app>GNOME</app> desktop are not available.</p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><p><app>Fedora</app></p></td>
        <td><p>18</p></td>
        <td><p>Yes, 3.8</p></td>
        <td><p>3.10 is the latest release of <app>GNOME</app>.</p></td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <note style="important">
      <p>It is recommended you <em>do not</em> install any non-stable distributions, even if you found the latest version of <app>GNOME</app> in it. Non-stable distributions can also be referred to as <em>preview</em>, <em>pre-release</em>, <em>release candidate (RC)</em>. These would be still largely untested whereas stable builds are meant for daily usage. Test builds are indicated with odd version numbers.</p>
    </note>

